    Using Alipay in China as a Tourist
I will visting CHINA at first time, what to use aplipay because I knew their are special version for non Chinese who have no chinese bank card
Thought for 69s

Yes, as a first-time visitor to China without a Chinese bank card, you can use Alipay through its international features designed for foreigners. This allows you to link an overseas credit or debit card directly for payments, or use the "Tour Card" (also called Tour Pass) option for a prepaid virtual card. These options have been simplified in recent years, with updates in 2025 making it easier for tourists, including expanded card support (like American Express) and better integration for transportation payments. I'll outline the steps below based on the latest guides—it's recommended to set this up before arriving in China to avoid any connectivity issues.

Option 1: Direct Linking of Your International Card (Recommended for Most Tourists – No Fees, Higher Limits)

This method charges your linked card on the spot for each transaction, with no top-up required. It's fee-free from Alipay's side (though your card issuer may charge foreign transaction fees), and there's no strict spending limit, but acceptance depends on the merchant.

  1. Download the Alipay App: Get it from your phone's app store (App Store for iOS or Google Play for Android). The app supports English—switch languages in settings if needed.
  2. Register an Account: Open the app, select "Sign Up," and use your international phone number (no Chinese number required). Verify with the SMS code sent to your phone. Set a strong password and enable biometric login (fingerprint or face ID) for security.
  3. Add Your Bank Card: Go to the "Me" tab (bottom right), tap "Bank Cards," then the "+" icon. Enter your card details manually or scan the card. You'll need to verify with a small authorization charge (refunded later). No identity verification is needed for basic use.
  4. Verify Identity if Needed for Higher Usage: For transactions over about 15,000 RMB (around $2,000 USD) total, or to unlock full features, upload your passport photo and a selfie in the app's verification section. This is quick and uses your phone's camera.
  5. Start Using Alipay:
    • To pay: Open the app, tap "Scan" to scan a merchant's QR code, or show your own QR code under "Pay" for them to scan.
    • Common uses: Shops, restaurants, taxis (via Didi app integration), metro/bus (scan QR at stations—now fully open to foreigners as of 2025), hotels, and online shopping on Taobao.
    • For transportation: Search "City Services" in the app for bus/metro codes in major cities like Beijing or Shanghai.

Supported Cards: Visa, Mastercard, UnionPay, Diners Club, JCB, and American Express (added support in 2025). Use a multi-currency card like Wise to avoid high conversion fees from your home bank.

Limitations:

  • Some small vendors or rural areas may not accept foreign-linked cards reliably—always carry some cash (RMB) as backup.
  • Daily/monthly transaction limits may apply based on your card issuer, typically around 5,000-10,000 RMB per day without verification.
  • You can't top up a balance or transfer money to others without a Chinese bank account.

Tips: Test a small payment (like buying a coffee) upon arrival to confirm it works. Enable notifications for transactions. If your phone lacks Google services (common issue in China), download the app via APK if needed, but stick to official sources.

Option 2: Using Tour Card (Prepaid Virtual Card – Good for Controlled Spending)

This creates a temporary virtual Chinese bank card (from Bank of Shanghai) inside Alipay, which you top up from your foreign card. It's more reliable for some merchants but has a 5% top-up fee and lower limits. Ideal if direct linking fails or for short trips.

  1. Download and Register: Follow steps 1-2 from Option 1.
  2. Access Tour Card: In the Alipay search bar, type "Tour Card" or "Tour Pass." Open the mini-app.
  3. Set Up and Top Up: Enter your details (name, passport number), choose a top-up amount (up to 10,000 RMB, about $1,400 USD), and pay with your foreign card. The 5% fee applies (e.g., 500 RMB fee for max top-up).
  4. Use It: Payments work the same as above—scan or show QR. The balance is used first.

Supported Cards for Top-Up: Visa, Mastercard, Diners Club, JCB.

Limitations:

  • Max 10,000 RMB per Tour Card; expires after 180 days, with unused funds refunded (minus fee).
  • Can't reload the same card—create a new one if needed.
  • Slightly higher cost due to the fee.

Tips: Use this if you're on a budget and want to limit spending. Refunds take 7-15 days after expiration.

General Advice for Your Trip

  • Backup Options: Set up WeChat Pay similarly (it also supports foreign cards) as a redundancy—many places accept both, but one might glitch. Carry 1,000-2,000 RMB in cash for emergencies, as not everywhere is cashless.
  • Fees and Currency: Expect 2-3% foreign transaction fees from your card; apps like Wise or Revolut minimize this. Alipay uses real-time exchange rates.
  • Security: Avoid public Wi-Fi for setup; use VPN if needed (but note VPNs are restricted in China). Report lost phones immediately via Alipay support.
  • Where It Works: Ubiquitous in cities for food, transport, shopping. In rural areas, cash is king.
  • Recent 2025 Changes: Better English support, 16 languages in the app, and e-CNY (digital yuan) integration for some payments, but stick to card linking for simplicity.

If you run into issues, Alipay has English customer support in the app, or ask at your hotel. Safe travels!
